@node "Introduction" "Introduction"

            @{b}@{u}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

GMAutoWrite.thor will automatically create email events at specified
intervals: either every N days or every day N!

It has been written originally for the Fidonet mailer EMS for my own use and
now it has been adapted to Thor using AutoReply.br from Neil Bothwick as a
guide.

It is intended to be called from Thor as @{i}Thor Startup ARexx script@{ui}.

Of course it needs to be correctly @{" installed " link "Installation" 0} and @{" configured " link "Configuration" 0} before you can
use it.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"

            @{b}Installation@{ub}

The three files in this archive must be copied to the correct directories for
GMAutoWrite.thor to work.

1) Copy GMAutoWrite.thor to <ThorPath>/rexx

2) Copy GMAutoWrite.guide to <ThorPath>/Docs

3) Copy GMAutoWrite.cfg to both ENV:Thor/ and ENVARC:Thor/

4) Edit the configuration file as needed (the sample tag is obviously
inactive)

5) Execute <ThorPath>/ConfigThor and put GMAutoWrite.thor as @{"THOR Startup" link "ConfigTHOR.guide/ARexx scripts" 0}
@{"arexx script" link "ConfigTHOR.guide/ARexx scripts" 0} into the Global configuration.

<ThorPath> is the directory containing Thor itself.
@endnode

@node "Configuration" "Creating a Configuration entry"

            @{b}Configuring GMAutoWrite@{ub}

When GMAutoWrite is called, it reads its configuration file and processes
every tags. If a tag is active and the time is due the message is created.

The options for each config are:

TAG   string
    System      string
    Conf        string
    Active      boolean
    Days        number
    BdyFile     string
    ToAddr      string
    ToName      string      (optional, default @{i}blank@{ui})
    Subject     string      (optional, default @{i}blank@{ui})
    SigFile     string      (optional, default @{i}blank@{ui})
    HdrFile     string      (optional, default @{i}blank@{ui})
    FtrFile     string      (optional, default @{i}blank@{ui})
    ExtPgm      string      (optional, default @{i}blank@{ui})
    ExtPgmType  number      (optional, default @{i}zero@{ui})
    Prog_PVT    number      (optional, default @{i}zero@{ui})
    Date_PVT    date        (optional, default @{i}zero@{ui})


Which do the following; please note that if a string contains one or more
spaces it must be enclosed in quotes (@{b}"@{ub}) and optionals options can, of course
:-), be omitted.


TAG
    It simply a mnemonic name, it must be one single word but it's not
    actually used for anything

SYSTEM
    The System in Thor that this applies to.

CONF
    The name of the email conference or newsgroup within that system.

Active
    A boolean value, 0 (false) or 1 (true), to let you disable a TAG without
    the need to removing it. If you need it again just change this to 1!

Days
    Can be a @{i}positive@{ui} number which means number of @{u}days between@{uu} message
    creation, or a @{i}negative@{ui} number which means the @{u}specific day@{uu} of the month.

    I.e. use 15 to post every 15 days or use -1 to post every 1st day!

    Beware that this is not a "cron-like" script: if you want to be sure that
    the second option will be processed you must execute GMAutoWrite every
    days!

BdyFile
    This is the main text of the message.

@{"ExtPgm" link "ExtPgm" 0}
    It's the external pgm that can be used to create the file specified with
    BdyFile. If used it must have a @{b}%F@{ub} somewhere, at run-time this
    placeholder will be replaced with the value of BdyFile.

@{"ExtPgmType" link "ExtPgm" 0}
    Set this to 1 if @{"ExtPgm" link "ExtPgm" 0} is a dos program or set it to 0 (or do not
    specify the keyword!) if @{"ExtPgm" link "ExtPgm" 0} is an ARexx program.

ToAddr
    The recipient address in the system format.

ToAddr
    The recipient name

Subject
    The subject line for the message.

SigFile
    Signature file to be appended to the message.

HdrFile
    File containing headers for the message.

FtrFile
    This file will be appended to the very end of the message.
    Could contain something like:
    "Message generated by the amazing GMAutoWrite.thor" ;-)

Prog_PVT
    This is an internal field used to keep track of the last post. Hint: to
    force a message write simply remove it or set it to @{i}zero@{ui}!

Date_PVT
    This is an internal field used to keep track of the last post. It's the
    Prog_PVT in human readable format...
    It's saved for your eyes only... :-)


Sample configuration

TAG   Test
   System    Internet
   Conf      it.test
   Active    0
   Days      30
   BdyFile   Mail:text/A_text_file.txt
   ToAddr    someone@domain.com
   Subject   "Don't read me!"
   Prog_PVT  7958
   Date_PVT  16/10/99
@endnode

@node "ExtPgm" "External program"

                @{b}@{u}External Program@{ub}@{uu}

The external program should allow only one argument which will be the filename
to be created.

The same apply to external program, to avoid any errors do not use the
function ARG to retrieve the parameter but use instead:

 @{b}parse arg FileName .@{ub}



Sample configuration file

TAG   TestExt
   System        Internet
   Conf          it.test
   Active        0
   Days          5
   BdyFile       T:TemporaryFile
   ToAddr        someone@domain.com
   Subject       "Text created with External Pgm!"
   ExtPgm        "test.rexx %f"
   ExtPgmType    0
@endnode

@node "Thor" "Using with Thor"

            @{b}Using GMAutoWrite from Thor@{ub}

You will need to run @{" ConfigThor " link "ConfigTHOR.guide/ARexx scripts" 0} to set this as THOR Startup arexx script.

At every Thor Startup the script will be executed and all the tags will be
read and processed creating messaging as instructed if it's the time.

You can have as many different tags as you like.
@endnode

